                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.24522/76: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Panama</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Warren</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-05-20T20:00:00-04:00"
                            >May 20, 1944—8 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>186. For Scotten. War and Navy Departments have approved latest Ecuadoran
                    counterdraft of Galápagos agreement, which is identical with that you brought
                    here with you except for omission of ratification clause in Preamble. Quito was
                    informed by telegram of May 17<note n="52" xml:id="d1041fn52">No. 430, not
                        printed.</note> that this Government will be ready to sign once certain
                    minor changes have been made in Spanish text. Embassy has been asked to
                    telegraph the Department if Ecuador is similarly ready, and been informed that
                    General Brett<note n="53" xml:id="d1041fn53">Lt. Gen. George H. Brett,
                        Commanding General, Caribbean Defense Command.</note> will then be requested
                    by War Department to send an officer to Quito to sign.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
